jobtitle: Analyze data and write white paper examining trends in data system usage rates
content: We are looking to hire an experienced data analyst with strong writing and visualization skills to write a brief white paper examining trends in usage data from our organization's data dashboards which are a tool provided to many staff across the organization. Successful completion of the project will include: 1) code for analysis in R, Stata or Python. 2) completed white paper with clear graphs and charts as well as a narrative that is accessible to individuals without a technical background 3) ability to work with imperfect, incomplete and sometimes messy data The individual completing this work will receive deidentified raw data on individual user logins to our dashboard application. There will be one observation per login event, as well as additional details about the user such as role (i.e. teacher, principal, district staff, etc.), school location, and other variables. You will also receive a summary file that includes all dashboard user accounts and the home site for each user, and this file will allow you to see individuals who have never logged on before. Below are sample questions that we seek to answer as a part of this white paper however we also require that the individual completing the project identify questions of interest and explore those. There is also a sample data file attached. •Overall, what does dashboard usage look like during the year? oWhat % of each user group are logging in on a monthly and biweekly basis? <U+F0A7>How many unique users are logging in each month? oIs higher principal user usage correlated to higher teacher or support user usage? oWhat times during the day are different users most logging in? oWere there different time periods during the year when dashboard usage spiked? When, and for which user groups? oAre people regularly coming back, or are they logging in once or twice every once in a while but not much more than that? oWhat differences emerge when we look at: <U+F0A7>Different roles (teacher, principal, district, support)? <U+F0A7>Different types of teachers (i.e. elementary vs. secondary, novice vs. experienced, % of students meeting growth, etc.)? <U+F0A7>Different schools? less

jobtitle: Write a query to detect movie release windows (gaps and islands problem)
content: Here is a query and a sample result: https://gist.github.com/gajus/e00e5d966b12f0d0f3a3f38b5e238e6d This query describes the number of movie showtimes in one country on different dates. The task is to determine movie release windows, e.g. Movie Blade Runner (1982) was originally released on 1982, 25th June (1st release window), then it had an extended cut release on 2002, 14th June (2nd release window), etc. We have a data of showtimes (country_id, movie_id, date, event_count). We need to add release_window to every date or NULL for pre-releases/ sparse screenings. Requirements: * A movie release is defined as any range of dates with one or more dates having more than 100 showtimes. * A movie release cut-off is any date with less than 5% of the maximum showtimes within that movie release. * Regardless of the number of count, dates with movie showtimes 30 days after the end of the last release window are ignored. In the sample dataset we see that it describes a single movie release. This movie release peaks on 2019-06-22 (5022 showtimes). We cut-off the showtimes that have less than 5% of the maximum showtimes within this movie release, i.e. we identify rows 3 to 17 (release_window=1), e.g. https://gist.github.com/gajus/49d3ae67ad4b221d38190eded4c000cf#file-result-csv-L3-L17. If there were more showtimes 30 days after this release window with any day having more than 100 showtimes, this would be the 2nd release window. The job is to write an SQL query that creates a materialized view that adds movie release window to every date of the showtime. Attached is a sample dataset for the last 3 months of UK cinema showtimes. less

jobtitle: Find all correlations
content: Find correlations in a data-set with 18 different variables. You can see how the data will be gathered in the attached spreadsheet. It is preferable, if you have some knowledge about SEO. The purpose of this correlations study is to find some correlations that should be used for understanding Amazon's algorithm. An example of a correlation that has been found, could be following: - The 1st organic search result has the keyword mentioned 10 times - Has in average 1k reviews - Has the keyword mentioned 10 times - The keyword is in always in the title of the 1st result - The average price for 1st result product is 20$ - and 1st and 3th quartiles Furthermore, please split up the correlation into general correlations (ex. number of words correlates positive/negative with number of pictures) and into specific based on the best ranking product. Example: #1st ranking product (keyword organic search number, 1) correlates positive/negative with Keyword in title. It may be difficult to know which correlations to look for, if you have no SEO experience or knowledge. If you have knowledge about SEO, you will also know that: "The product that ranks 48th on a given search does not have the keyword in the title" is relevant and "Number of words correlates with the keyword's presence in the review section" is not relevant. Another example of a relevant correlation: The worst ranking product has 1200 words in the description and the keyword mentioned 10 times, whereas the best ranking product only have 400 words and the keyword mentioned 2 times. I think the best results will in relevant cases be found by using smaller parts of the data set to find correlations. Example: Products from the keyword category - "office supplies": The correlation for amount of keywords in title and their ranking is positive/negative. Another thing, which I think we could be able to find: Keywords with 3 words in it has a correlation close to 1.00 with the keyword in the title. This is also something that is exciting to find. You can look at sheet 1 & 2 for inspiration. less

jobtitle: Event Study analysis in R - Stock Price Reaction to M&A announcements

The goal of the analysis would be to estimate the cumulative abnormal return for roughly 1000 cases. To achieve this, one needs to have a market model (regression of past stock returns against benchmark index returns) in order to estimate the "normal returns" for the acquiring companies. The actually achieved returns during the event period are then compared against the "normal returns" to estimate abnormal returns. These abnormal returns should in the next step be scrutinized with a t-test to test for significance. Two options with regards to deliverable: 1. Writing a new R script that estimates the market model, calculating the delta of actual vs. estimated returns, running t-tests to check for significance of findings for approx. 1000 cases. 2. jobtitle: Analysing laser scan maps using QGIS
content: We’re digitising buildings with laser-scanning equipment and get “point-cloud” files out of it. Sometimes our scanning team misses areas, sometimes the data quality is bad. We want to know which areas we missed and which areas have we captured. I have a video explaining the process in full detail: https://www.dropbox.com/s/k5qvwzto43carz5/QGIS%20How%20to%20extract%20missing%20area%20maps.mov?dl=0 You will need the following tools for the operation: • QGIS with Spatialite and GeoTIFF support • Dropbox and a Dropbox account – we’ll be sharing files through Dropbox. For each building we will make available to you: • 6-band GeoTIFF files in which band 5 contains the captured point count the given floor that we will base our analysis on. • Spatialite databases that have been created from auto-converting CAD files. • A (logarithmic) color ramp configuration to apply as style for the GeoTIFF files. You will execute the following tasks (as explained in training videos) for each building (we will call it a “batch”): 1. You will create a QGIS project file You will execute the following tasks for each floor in the building: 2. You will create a layer group identifying the floor. As floor label you should use the same labels of the GeoTIFF file. The GeoTIFF files are named as follows: {Building-ID}_{Substructure-ID}_{Floor-Level-ID}.tiff 3. You will load the GeoTIFF file and assign the “Arbitrary Transverse Mercator m” projection in meters. You will apply the color ramp as a style as shown in the video. 4. You will load the Spatialite database and assign the “Arbitrary Transverse Mercator mm” projection (in millimeters). You will enable or disable vector layers until you got a good view. 5. You will create a new POLYGON layer in the Spatialite database (in “Arbitrary Transverse Mercator m” projection) called “missing” and mark up all areas missing (white) the the GeoTIFF file. Ignore crossed areas in the Spatialite layers and other areas explained to be excluded in the video. Each area gets a “label” field using the following naming scheme: {Building-ID} {Substruction-ID} L-{Floor-Level-ID} missing {running number} The running number is to be increased for each missing area marked up. The style should be backwards hashed and the label should be clearly visible on the map. 6. You will create a new POLYGON layer in the Spatialite database (in “Arbitrary Transverse Mercator m” projection) called “captured” and mark up the area that have been captured. Please be intelligent about it: You don’t need to create inner rings to markup holes and if the GeoTIFF ends close to Spatialite line vectors, use point snapping. The style should be forward hashed. 7. You will create a new “print layout” (paper format: A4 landscape) that displays the “missing areas” of this floor as shown in the video. Do not include the “captured” layer in the PDF. Each print layout should contain the following label on top of the page: {Building-ID} {Substructure-ID} L-{Floor-ID} You will save the print layout as PDF under the same name as the label above. The purpose of this PDF is: I want to give the map to my scanning team, so they know which areas they have to capture again. The missing area labels must be easily readable, so when I talk to them we can refer to specific areas by their label. Deliverables: • QGIS project file • “captured” and “missing” layers in each floor’s Spatialite database. • PDF file for each floor showing missing areas (like in the video). All deliverables will be shared through Dropbox or in rare cases through upwork file upload. We are hiring multiple freelancers for the job. We will be giving each one of you initially a small sample. The better the quality and the speed of your work, the more work we will assign to you from our backlog. In your application to this job, please specify: • How long have you worked with QGIS software? Do you have any question about what was shown in the video? • Have you worked with point-clouds before? How? What software were you using? Freelancers and agencies who do not answer the questions above in their application will be silently ignored. Please go through the training materials and share with me your questions. If you don’t have any question, I will assign you the first batch as a paid trial run. Please provide me with the following details to set up up for the job: • The email address for your Dropbox account. I will be sharing a folder with you for each registration job that you work on. • Which version of QGIS are you intending to use? Have you checked that it supports Spatialite? less

jobtitle: Real Estate ML Project Python/Jupyter/Pandas/Plot.ly/Random Forests/scikit learn
content: Hello and thanks for taking a look at my project. I am interested in looking at my City’s residential property market using Python/Jupyter notebooks, Pandas, Matplotlib, Folium, Plot.ly, SciKit-Learn, Seaborn, Random forests, scikit-learn and yelp fusion API in order to try to understand: - The distribution of sold prices of apartments and houses - Identify popular areas - Pin point locations where properties tend to be cheaper than average - Predict the prices of properties Here is an example of what I'm looking to do https://towardsdatascience.com/going-dutch-how-i-used-data-science-and-machine-learning-to-find-an-apartment-in-amsterdam-part-def30d6799e4 see https://github.com/rafaelpierre/going-dutch the pynb file etc. Also see https://towardsdatascience.com/going-dutch-part-2-improving-a-machine-learning-model-using-geographical-data-a8492b67b885. I have the data available, no scraping required. Requirements: - Data merge and clean up. See attached size and price paid spreadsheet. This is a record of properties that have sold, and their sizes along with some other information. Use attached 'open_postcode_geo' file to add long/lat coordinates to all records in 'price' sheet by matching postcodes. In 'size' sheet find all duplicate addresses, and keep the most recent versions based on INSPECTION_DATE' field. Disregard the older duplicates in 'size'. Now use fuzzy matching or any preferred method to merge the two sheets 'size' and 'price paid' based on address. The relevant fields for this are: ADDRESS1, ADDRESS2, ADDRESS3, POSTCODE, LOCAL_AUTHORITY_LABEL, in 'size' postcode, address1, address2, address3, address4, city, in 'price paid' The final result should be the 'price paid' sheet populated with the information from 'size' sheet. Once this is done, this 'size' sheet will not be required. - Create a Pandas DataFrame. Show some basic statistics e.g. quartiles, minimum, max and mean values for most of the variables. The key variables are 'total_floor_area', 'number_habitable_rooms' and 'price'. Convert date_time fields to integers, using unix epoch or similar. Snapshot data using plot.ly box plot. (see jupyter file in link above for how to do these). - Assist in interpreting the data: Deviation from normal distribution. Skewness and kurtosis. Seaborn pairplots to visually show relationships between variables. Seaborn heat maps to plot pearson correlation values between variables. Drop variables with negligible correlations. Zoom into variables with correlations, both log scale and non scaled. Price v latitude and size v latitude to locate good area for acquisitions. Folium visualization on map, open source mapping e.g. openstreetmap. - Analysis: Random forests. Try to predict 'price'. Training set composed of 70% of data set and test set of 30% of data set. R2 score to check prediction accuracy. - Proximity to amenities. Query yelp’s fusion API to get data on places of interest (POI’s) for ten amenities (e.g. groceries, cafe's etc). Calculate distance from those POI’s. Count number of POI’s within a certain radius. Box plots to see how these variables price. Heatmap pearson correlation matrix to identify significant linear relationships (if any). Train the model and see how it performs by running analysis step again. I would like to try 3 different machine learning algorithms/systems, example regression trees, neural networks, support vector machines and select the best performing one of the 3 based on lowest mean absolute error. less

jobtitle: BigQuery Expert needed for consultation
content: We own a social network web application, that guests, free members and subscribers visit daily to interact with other members of the community, and we would like to be able to track all the events that they generate while doing so. Amongst those events are : following other community members, sending chat messages, giving “likes” to other members etc, all the type of events that you would expect to encounter on a social network (we have a detailed list). We are looking for a BigQuery expert to help us structure the tables and data in order to achieve an optimal setup, both in terms of querying costs & speed, as well as easy scalability and adaptability. The goal is to create a data lake that we can analyse and extract insights and hypothesis from to create new experiments (ab tests) that optimize the product and increase retention as well as conversion. We created a first draft of what the database schema could look like, with nested columns that contain user properties for each event, essentially each record added to the table would contain : - information about the event itself - information about the user that generated it. - timestamp We would like you to take a look and advise us on : - What data to store and what data to ignore ? - How to structure the table for scale and flexibility ? - How to structure the regular querying of the table for optimal cost ? --- Daily aggregation to google sheet ? --- Daily querying from Data Studio ? If you think you can help : please start your application message with "iambigdata" to show that you have read the job description. Here are some queries/questions we would like to use this data for : - How many chat messages did a free member send before subscribing ? --- Same question for members that came from a specific source (user property field) - How many likes does a free member give on average before subscribing ? - How does that average compare to the one of free members that didn’t subscribe ? - How many days on average does it take a free member to subscribe ? --- Same question for members that added their avatar on their sign up date; sign up date+1, .. where is the best correlation with the user subscribing ? - Cohorts of the user lifetime value (and retention) based on having seen a particular page - Cohorts of the user lifetime value based on having uploaded an avatar picture - What succession of events generated the fastest path (and highest rate) to subscription ? - What event is the best predictor of a user subscribing ? what event is the best predictor of a user not subscribing ? We are looking for someone that speaks english and can do the initial consultation during a live video call. less

jobtitle: Data developer needed to do some G Sheet and Data Studio Dashboard work using Supermetrics
content: We run a marketing analytics agency in Calgary (CMO4Hire.com) that makes extensive use of G Suite and Google Data Studio to help our clients (through our software www.dbmms.io). We have a number of client dashboards that are updated either directly from the data source (Analytics, Ads) and we set most of that up. Many of our dashboards are more complex than that. These require us to get data into a G Sheet and then flows into a Data Studio Template. We use Supermetrics as the connector in G Sheets, where we bring in daily data from a number of sources, do some processing in G Sheets, and then offer it to our clients usually through Data Studio Templates. We have an immediate need to find an application data developer who is familiar with G Sheets, App Script, and Supermetrics (although that's pretty easy to learn). We'd also like to find someone who has Biq Query experience, and can eventually help us connect our G Sheets applications to Big Query tables, off loading some processing time (and big data). Right now we have several dashboards that are breaking ... aren't updating from Supermetrics ... which happens far too frequently (haha), but that's the way it goes. So, initially your work will be about fixing those problems as they arise. You will also start helping all our clients (and new clients) getting set up on our dashboard system, and eventually deeper programming in Big Query once you understand how we approach things. This is part-time, piecemeal work that we will assign to you, for which you'll be paid hourly. We are looking for a flexible individual (NOT AN AGENCY!) for a long-term relationship where you are one of the people who are on a team serving clients. jobtitle: Technical Research: What words in source-code show that a company uses salesforce?
content: The ideal deliverable is a detailed report (or csv) of words, patterns (typically found in HTML code) that would indicate any particular company is using salesforce. Some examples I've found so far are: - if their sourecode refers to pardot they're probably using Salesforce - if their source refers to sfdc or 'salesforce' they're definitely using salesforce - if their source code refers to web-to-lead they are using salesforce - if their careers site refers to salesforce they're probably using salesforce - if they have have a dedicated employee salesforce login site So those are a handful of things I've discovered so far but I think there are probably 100 (or at least a bunch) more tricks that could be used. Once I can make a comprehensive list of these tricks, I can then hire a data-scraping expert to incorporate all of these into a tool to help determine which sites are or are not likely to be running salesforce. Your job is just to help with the 'tricks' and keywords though (some of these keywords may be 'salesforce plug-ins or third-party tools that rely on salesforce btw!). less

jobtitle: Modelling Distributions
content: Hypothetically as a part of our philanthropy efforts we are looking to distribute funds E.g. $1,000,000 total funding amount. We want to give away these funds during discrete periods, where we provide a fixed amount per person per period, until all the funds are exhausted Period 1: Person A -> Receives X Amount Period 2: Person A -> Receives Y Amount Person B -> Receives Y Amount Period 3: Person A -> Receives Y Amount Person B -> Receives Y Amount Person C -> Receives Y Amount Note the number of people asking for a donation each period can vary and the same person can keep coming back for each period asking for a donation. These are the constraints of the Model: How long will the funds last as the number of people seeking donations per period increase. Model different growth rates of people seek donations to see when funds are exhausted. Determine efficient $ distribution each period such that no one person can gain > 2.5% of the total funding amount Provide relationship between funds distributed per person each period vs number of people seeking donations vs periods till funds are exhausted Required: Provide a model which adheres the contraints above. The model must include raw analysis , graphs and justification, with explicit instructions to reproduce the results in the program of your choice: r, python, excel. less

jobtitle: Investment simulator and back test
content: We want someone to build a simulator that buys and sells equities based on pre-set rules, and back tests against market history to calculate returns. Markets: * UK, Germany, Netherlands, Finland, Sweden, Italy Each day buy according to the following rules: * Dividend yield between 7% and 12% * Market cap greater than EUR 300m and lower than EUR 1 billion * For each company ensure that dividend payments are sustainable: * For last twelve months, the ratio of dividend paid / (free cash flow + one-off costs) < 0.8 Do not buy if: * Revenue has fallen by more than 15% over 2 years * Ratio of revenue/EBITDA has risen by more than 15% over 2 years For each day sell according to the following rules: * Dividend yield is lower than 6% * Dividend yield has fallen by more than 25% since purchase * Dividend yield has risen by more than 15% since purchase We would like for the strategy to be tested against a reasonable time period, at least 5 years (ideally as long as you can do it). If any of these countries is particularly hard to get data for, please tell us and we will consider removing it. We are happy for you to use any tools you’d like to write this software. jobtitle: Data Analytics
content: Title: Contract Content Analyst - a distant job Description: A contract analyst works with incentive agreement documents. These are legal business documents describing the incentive model established between an airline (or a group of affiliated airlines) and a travel agency. The analyst is required to: 1. Correctly identify the key elements in each incentive plan. For example: start and end date, incentive target types (e.g. coupons sold, revenue in specific currency), incentive payment types (e.g. percentage of qualifying revenue, $ per coupon, fixed incentive), specific terms and conditions related to inclusion for target and for payment (e.g. specific geographies and fare classes included/excluded, specific flight codes or operating airlines), linkage between plans (e.g. one plan is a safety plan, operating only in case the agency failed to meet the minimal target in some other plan) 2. Identify and interact with the customer, in English, to obtain any missing information, such as last year's sales in case of a year-over-year growth target. 3. Correctly model the plan's parameters in a computer-readable file in JSON format. Upload the JSON file to a staging system, and ensure it's correctly displayed in the product. 4. Correctly report to the engineering team any plan characteristics which could not be correctly modeled due to shortcomings of the existing JSON format. Work with the team to suggest extension to the JSON format. Required Experience: Law student with a technical background OR a technology student / junior with aviation or legal background OR travel agent with a mind for technology Company: A startup company from San Francisco, Tel Aviv, and Kiev. Its mission is to make airline-agencies commercial relationships stronger and more effective. That, by our practice, creates a better profit for both sides. Product: a data-driven platform allowing travel agencies and airlines to track incentive plans, in real time, to optimize sales and profit margins. less

jobtitle: Pathway analysis
content: The project involves the characterization of proteins from tissue samples of breast cancer, seeking to characterize the carcinogenesis differences in protein expression between normal and tumor tissue.The protein extracts from these tissue specimens are complex. In an effort to reduce the complexity, the protein extracts were subjected to molecular weight fractionation via electrophoretic separation through the SDS-PAGE material in the tubular environment. All fractions were produced in the liquid phase (GELFREE). The results of such separation are 12 fractions (MW) in the liquid phase for each examined protein extract. Raw data generated by LC-MS/MS-LTQ-Orbitrap Fusion were used to interrogate the identity of protein through PEAKS software V.7.5 using the standard workflow. The parameters used in protein identification were Homo sapiens for the database, trypsin for enzyme, Carbamidomethylation, and Oxidation (M) for fixed. The list of the proteins that have been obtained is attached. I need to do the pathway analysis for those proteins and also do a write-up ( a report on the analysis which includes figures similar to the examples provided). less

jobtitle: Need a scoring algorithm to rank products
content: Looking for someone with a math and data science background to create a scoring algorithm to assign a score out of 100 to products. There are about 10 different dimensions on which the product score would be based, and for each of these dimensions there are a few possible options. So what we'd like to do is assign a point value or weight to each option, and then create a scoring formula that will combine them all and output a score out of 100. For example: Product Feature A: -Good = 1 point -Better = 2 points -Best 2.5 points Product Feature B -Good = 0 points -Better = 1 point -Best = 3 points etc. We will provide a detailed list of the different dimensions and details on how we'd like to value them. Also note that the scores should be bell-curved to be mostly distributed in the 65 to 95 range. So the formula needs to ensure that scores never exceed 99, and generally should not be below 50-60. Please include any similar projects you've worked on that you think would be relevant, what your general approach would be, and any questions you have! less

jobtitle: Expert to setup Google Analytics to track install conversions/funnels; AdSense & AdWords exp a plus
content: Expert to setup Google Analytics to track install conversions; AdSense & AdWords knowledge a plus I need someone’s help to fix/setup Google Analytics. I have a couple of browser extensions that I want to track installs (“Conversions/Goals”) for in Google Analytics. I have two browser extensions, which are on two different domains and then there’s a 3rd domain that is also involved that displays search results for one of the browser extensions. I think I need to simplify things and get rid of the 3rd domain, consolidating that into the same domain used by the one browser extension. I have Google Analytics setup, however it’s not setup properly and I am not an expert by any means. I have two extensions at the moment, but there will be more in the future with more domains, so I think I should be using Google Tag Manager, but you would tell me if hired. I need help. Things I want to track/know: - How many people click this big ‘continue’ button on my primary domain? How many try to exit my install process? - How many hit track_install? (which is a url that doesn’t exist on my domain, however the Google Chrome Store allows me to input my domain and will feed by Analytics when an install occurs in the Google Chrome Store of my extension) - How many hit /webstore/detail/… (which is again, another URL that Google Chrome Store will hit my analytics with so that I can track conversions/rates of how my Google Chrome Store description page is working for me -- thus, if I try different text or screenshots, it could affect my conversion rate) - How many people hit /success/ (prob same amount as track_install) [The /success/ page is called after the user installs extension1. We then call that same /success/ page after the user installs extension2. Both times we hit one of our domains for that url, the thinking is that tracking the conversions will be easier. If you work with me, I’d like your thoughts on this, as well as our other urls in order to ensure proper conversion tracking] - Setup a funnel for the 2-4 steps involved for the user to install both of my extensions (the How many people uninstall? (When they do uninstall either extension, we call an uninstall URL on both domains) - How many people hit my websites and I present an error page to them, because I do not support their browser? (My extensions are only for Firefox and Chrome desktop web browsers) - I have another subdomain on one of the domains, and then this 3rd domain, which both display search results to users. I’m thinking of removing the 3rd domain, and the subdomain on the other domain, and simply putting the search results at ‘/search/’ on both domains; I think this would simplify things, but wasn’t really thinking about that at the time we developed these. I’d like to discuss this with you if you’re hired. - How many searches happened today on each site? (I use Google Custom Search Engine -- CSE) I have not bought adwords ads yet, but I plan to do that and want everything ready to do that, so that I can know when certain adgroups/keywords are not converting for me (and vice-versa, which ones are working great and I should spend more). You don’t need to know AdWords much, but you should have experience with Analytics accounts that have done buys using AdWords, Bing, and maybe other ad sources. less

jobtitle: Programmer needed to create a script using an open source software for in-depth data analysis
content: Objective: To determine if the order in which applications are made, and the time between signup and applications, influences conversion rate and transaction value. We are also interested in where applications to certain lenders fall in a sequence, and whether that application was made in isolation, or as part of a cluster of applications. Background: Our service connects users with various lending options based on their profile. The average number of applications per user is approximately 1.6, which has a skewed distribution to a long tail that can stretch to 10 or more applications. A user will sometimes apply to several options in 1 single sessions, and sometimes can wait several months before applying again. We are trying to gain insights from the order and time differences in which the applications are made to ascertain if certain lending options should be presented at different times, or not at all. ‘Success’ for our business is measured in Transactions, ie: the application leads to an approval and there is commission earned. The magnitude of the commission is secondary to whether there is a commission at all. Data Fields: ApplicationID - integer string - unique for each application UserID - integer string - unique for each user StatusID - numerical code for status of the application, which is one of 6 possible codes. User Created Date - Date and time stamp - when the user joined the platform Application Created Date - Date and time stamp - when the application was created Year, Month, Day, Weekday, Week# - simple breakdown of Application Created Date into components LenderID - integer string - unique numerical identifier for each lender PartnerID - integer string - unique numerical identifier for each affiliate partner Credit Score ID - numerical indicator (from 1 to 5) denoting the user’s credit score band (eg: Fair, Good, Excellent etc.) Transaction Value - currency string - value of the commission arising from an application, if any. Transaction Date - when the transaction occurred App. Rec. - if the application was created during the month-end reconciliation process. Any row where this value = 1 has a Transaction Date that is earlier than the Application Date, and thus any analysis comparing those 2 fields should exclude these rows. less

If you can use ""ART - ANALYSIS OF RESOURCES FOR TRIALS(survival version 1.1.0, 10 December 2013) by Abdel G Babiker, Patrick Royston & Friederike Barthel, MRC Clinical Trials Unit at UCL, London WC1V 6LJ, UK."" jobtitle: Data Analysis using R
content: Have to select a dataset, come up with a question to answer and do analysis in R. Do data wrangling, exploration/visuals, draw a conclusion. Details: -Create 2 charts exploring the data with respect to the prediction variable (label) -Create a hypothesis and perform a t.test to reject or fail to reject your hypothesis. -Split the data into training set and testing set for each model and wrangle the data as desired. -Create 2 prediction models of your chosen type (regression | classification), with at least one multivariate model including visualizing the results of each model. -Compare the performance of your models -Include a written analysis of your prediction referencing using data to support your conclusions. All codes should run in R. Nothing complicated. Throw a few simple simple slides to summarize the assignment that can be presented: 1. Situation or problem statement: describe what the situation is, what you are trying to figure out and why. 2. Key Question(s): Describe the key question(s) in terms of the variable your team selected to spotlight. 3. Data Source(s): Provide a full description of where the data comes from. (Can use https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets.php (Links to an external site.)Links to an external site. OR https://toolbox.google.com/datasetsearch (Links to an external site.)Links to an external site.) 4. Data Wrangling: What you did to organize the data: · Removed columns, Converted columns, Transform data: gather(); summarize(); distinct(); sort(); and any changes needed to prepare for model training 5. Data Exploration/ Visuals: Provide a few of the visuals you used to explore the data. 6. Conclusions: Describe the final solution that answers the key questions, including the accuracy of at least two prediction models. less

jobtitle: DeltaDNA data analyst / BI expert - Strong in SQL
content: Your Role As part of a lean startup and the first team member responsible for data and BI, you need to be a "jack of all trades" and willing to learn quickly, take on responsibility and multiple functions. The primary role we are looking for is as a Data Analyst across our portfolio of slots games. However, the ideal candidate will also be able to taken on responsibilities of Game Economist as well as Product Manager (will be reflected in salary). Data Analyst By analyzing data, you should be able to understand how players are playing our games and draw conclusions for improvement in the product in order to improve player retention and monetization. Game Economist Build, evaluate and tweak the economy of the game in order to drive engagement and monetization. You will be responsible for the game economy model and currency pricing in our games. You should be able to take over existing economies and improve them, as well as building economy from scratch for products. Product Manager By looking at the data, you should develop strategies, A/B tests and features to improve engagement and monetization. MUST HAVE: Strong SQL skills. Access to both iOS and Android phones - so that can have access to our live games. VERY IMPORTANT: Experience as data analyst on mobile games BIG BENEFIT: Experience with DeltaDNA NICE TO HAVE: Experience as data analyst SPECIFICALLY on mobile social casino SLOTS games Degree in a relevant field (Statistics, Mathematics, Economics, Physics, Engineering, Computer Science). Experience with game economy, product management. AREAS OF RESPONSIBILITY: You will take ownership of analyzing the data in our games and make improvements based on this data. Your ultimate goal is to improve player engagement and monetization KPIs. Write SQL queries to deep-dive into our data and come up with actionable improvements based off this data. Build dashboards for easy visualization of KPIs (and make business / product decisions based off analysis). Build and modify event schema structure for our games in order to be able to get the data you need. Work with developers to ensure successful implementation of event schema. Skilfully draw conclusions from data and provide recommendations for further development of games and features. Split testing: decide on and prioritize elements of game to A/B test; design A/B tests; review results and propagate winners that are statistically significant. Product: review the data and the product itself, make decisions on changes to the product in order to improve KPIs - in particular engagement and monetization. Game economy: Evaluate the game economy to ensure that there are no "leaks"; build and balance the economy for new features; tweak the game economy to improve KPIs. User Acquisition: assist our user acquisition efforts by analyzing early data (day 3, day 7) and helping to decide which campaigns to scale or cut back; estimate future LTV per traffic source. Own the BI infrastructure (data management and visualization capabilities) - make recommendations and oversee implementation of improvements as needed. PERSONAL ATTRIBUTES: Good spoken and written English. Willing to take on and assume responsibility. Eager to learn and able to self-learn in areas where you are currently weak. Independent and self motivated. Trust worthy. Should be capable of working between 9am to 5pm Tel Aviv time. OUR CURRENT ANALYTICS TOOLS: DeltaDNA, data dump to Amazon S3. Facebook Analytics GameAnalytics About us: Megarama Games was founded in 2015 as the brainchild of two entrepreneurs in the mobile space. This is the second startup for the founders, one a former medical doctor turned entrepreneur and the other a world-leading cybersecurity expert. In their previous startup, the founders produced and published games and apps of different genres across multiple platforms. From their extensive testing they found repeated and sustainable success in the social casino genre and decided to form Megarama Games in order to focus on this exclusively on this genre and build a world-class slots game that players will fall in love with. Megarama owns a portfolio of slots games, with Slots WOW™ being one of the most well-known. Megarama's games have been downloaded millions of times cross Apple and Google Play and the games are commonly within the top 100 in their categories in the major markets (United States and Australia). The company is fully remote, with team members spread across Europe and Asia. less

jobtitle: Data Analyst with experience in mobile free-to-play games (DeltaDNA Experience Preferred!)
content: Your Role As part of a lean startup and the first team member responsible for data, you need to be a "jack of all trades" and willing to learn quickly, take on responsibility and multiple functions. The primary role we are looking for is as a Data Analyst across our portfolio of slots games. However, the ideal candidate will also be able to taken on responsibilities of Game Economist as well as Product Manager (will be reflected in salary). Data Analyst By analyzing data, you should be able to understand how players are playing our games and draw conclusions for improvement in the product in order to improve player retention and monetization. Game Economist Build, evaluate and tweak the economy of the game in order to drive engagement and monetization. You will be responsible for the game economy model and currency pricing in our games. You should be able to take over existing economies and improve them, as well as building economy from scratch for products. Product Manager By looking at the data, you should develop strategies, A/B tests and features to improve engagement and monetization. MUST HAVE: Strong SQL skills. Access to both iOS and Android phones - so that can have access to our live games. VERY IMPORTANT: Experience as data analyst on mobile games BIG BENEFIT: Experience with DeltaDNA NICE TO HAVE: Experience as data analyst SPECIFICALLY on mobile social casino SLOTS games Degree in a relevant field (Statistics, Mathematics, Economics, Physics, Engineering, Computer Science). Experience with game economy, product management. AREAS OF RESPONSIBILITY: You will take ownership of analyzing the data in our games and make improvements based on this data. Your ultimate goal is to improve player engagement and monetization KPIs. Write SQL queries to deep-dive into our data and come up with actionable improvements based off this data. Build dashboards for easy visualization of KPIs (and make business / product decisions based off analysis). Build and modify event schema structure for our games in order to be able to get the data you need. Work with developers to ensure successful implementation of event schema. Skilfully draw conclusions from data and provide recommendations for further development of games and features. Split testing: decide on and prioritize elements of game to A/B test; design A/B tests; review results and propagate winners that are statistically significant. Product: review the data and the product itself, make decisions on changes to the product in order to improve KPIs - in particular engagement and monetization. Game economy: Evaluate the game economy to ensure that there are no "leaks"; build and balance the economy for new features; tweak the game economy to improve KPIs. User Acquisition: assist our user acquisition efforts by analyzing early data (day 3, day 7) and helping to decide which campaigns to scale or cut back; estimate future LTV per traffic source. Own the BI infrastructure (data management and visualization capabilities) - make recommendations and oversee implementation of improvements as needed. PERSONAL ATTRIBUTES: Good spoken and written English. Willing to take on and assume responsibility. Eager to learn and able to self-learn in areas where you are currently weak. Independent and self motivated. Trust worthy. Should be capable of working between 9am to 5pm Tel Aviv time. OUR CURRENT ANALYTICS TOOLS: DeltaDNA, data dump to Amazon S3. Facebook Analytics GameAnalytics About us: Megarama Games was founded in 2015 as the brainchild of two entrepreneurs in the mobile space. This is the second startup for the founders, one a former medical doctor turned entrepreneur and the other a world-leading cybersecurity expert. In their previous startup, the founders produced and published games and apps of different genres across multiple platforms. From their extensive testing they found repeated and sustainable success in the social casino genre and decided to form Megarama Games in order to focus on this exclusively on this genre and build a world-class slots game that players will fall in love with. Megarama owns a portfolio of slots games, with Slots WOW™ being one of the most well-known. Megarama's games have been downloaded millions of times cross Apple and Google Play and the games are commonly within the top 100 in their categories in the major markets (United States and Australia). The company is fully remote, with team members spread across Europe and Asia. less

jobtitle: Programmer required for non-linear data analysis
content: Scenario: We produce a bulk amount of product each day, ranging from 20,000 to 100,000 units. Each unit is scored for quality. (Product score) This score ranges from 0.01 to 30. We then separate and package these products into the 5 different sorts (or grades) Each sort has a different market value. Sort 5 is the most valuable and Sort 1 the least valuable Some products are eligible to be placed in any of the 5 categories. Obviously, we would like the to separate the products so that the overall mix of sorts is the most valuable. However, as a population, each sort must satisfy two requirements. The Average Product Score for that product must meet a minimum criteria and the 5%ile score for that product must meet a minimum criteria. If you move a product from one category to another, it changes the average and 5%ile property for both categories. We know the distribution of the Product scores before we undertake the sorting process. (Think of it like a bucket of marbles and we know the Product score of each of the marbles before we sort them) We are looking for a programmer to write code that calculates the optimum sorting set-points for each of the sorts that maximizes the value whilst meeting the minimum value Average Product Score for each sort and the minimum value 5%ile Product Score for each sort. A functional specification is attached. A run time limit for running the code is not specified, as we would like to discuss the trade off between optimisation time and run time. Budget amount is set as minimum. Happy to discuss costs. less
